{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646788"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:35:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:35:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18206"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18206"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.15,0.35,0.3,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10920"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73816"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10920"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18206"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59292"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5296"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25389"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73816"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESome immunosuppressive drugs work by inhibiting the proliferation of activated lymphocytes. One such mechanism involves the inhibition of pyrimidine synthesis, which is crucial for DNA replication and cell division.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following drugs inhibits dihydro-orotate dehydrogenase, thereby affecting pyrimidine synthesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Leflunomide","Hydroxychloroquine","Sulfasalazine","Methotrexate","Penicillamine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeflunomide\u003C/strong\u003E inhibits dihydro-orotate dehydrogenase, an enzyme necessary for the de novo synthesis of pyrimidines. This inhibition leads to a decrease in the proliferation of activated lymphocytes, making it effective in treating autoimmune conditions like rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydroxychloroquine\u003C/strong\u003E - This drug works by interfering with lysosomal activity and antigen presentation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESulfasalazine\u003C/strong\u003E - This drug is a combination of sulfapyridine and 5-aminosalicylic acid, used primarily for its anti-inflammatory effects\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E - This drug inhibits dihydrofolate reductase, affecting folate metabolism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPenicillamine\u003C/strong\u003E - This drug is a chelating agent used in conditions like Wilson\u0027s disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Leflunomide inhibits dihydro-orotate dehydrogenase, an enzyme involved in pyrimidine synthesis, leading to reduced proliferation of activated lymphocytes.","Inhibition of pyrimidine synthesis is a mechanism used by some immunosuppressive drugs to control autoimmune diseases.","Leflunomide is used in the treatment of rheumatoid arthritis due to its immunosuppressive effects."],"references":["Padda IS, Goyal A. Leflunomide. 2023 Jun 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491731.","Tian H, Cronstein BN. Understanding the mechanisms of action of methotrexate: implications for the treatment of rheumatoid arthritis. Bull NYU Hosp Jt Dis. 2007;65(3):168-73. PMID: 17922664","Waller, D. G., \u0026 Hitchings, A. W. (2021). Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book: Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Tashjian, A. H., \u0026 Armstrong, E. J. (2011). Principles of pharmacology: the pathophysiologic basis of drug therapy. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Queremel Milani DA, Davis DD. Pain Management Medications. 2023 Jul 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809527"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59292"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18206"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59292"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T04:34:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T04:36:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10920"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73816"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationship